ortant aspect of visual attention is the flexible capacity to prioritize external information for processing. Through this capacity, the human brain can process the same external information differently on different occasions, according to the current behavioural goals. Recently, it has been demonstrated that the human brain (specifically the posterior parietal cortices [PPC]) can prioritize information for selection according to its relevant saliency. Interestingly, findings also suggest lateralization of salience-based selection with the right PPC relevant for selection of salient information and the left PPC relevant for selection of information low in salience (in the face of irrelevant but more salient distracting information). However, it is not clear how ?saliency-based? selection is implemented in the brain ? for example, how quickly can we select high and low saliency stimuli, and how do brain regions interact in these different forms of selection? This study aims to investigate this question by focusing on the time-course of salience selection. Utilizing the high temporal resolution of event related potentials (ERP), the study asks whether selection of low vs. high saliency could be differentiated also by its time-course. This information may then facilitate understanding of the implementation of selective mechanisms in the brain.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>74330</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutpu